If you only have commas between variables, and you're sure that there are no commas within individual questions or answers, then using `.split(", ")` is appropriate. However, if there's a possibility that a comma could appear within a question or answer, then things get a bit more complicated.

One way to differentiate between "real commas" (those that separate variables) and "text commas" (those within the text of a variable) is to use a more unique delimiter when storing or exporting your data. For example, instead of separating variables with a comma, you could use a sequence like `|||` or `;;;` which is unlikely to appear in regular text.

If you don't have control over the format of the data and need to differentiate between "real commas" and "text commas", then you'll need a more sophisticated parsing method. One approach is to look for patterns. For instance, if a comma is followed by a space and a capital letter, it might be a "real comma". But this isn't foolproof.

